Feb 22
Release Notes
Master Configuration: How to Tune Your Settings

Open the indicator settings (click the gear icon next to the script name) to access your control panel. Here is exactly what every dial and switch does.

1. Signal Sensitivity (The Core Engine)

This section controls how strict the algorithm is before it allows a "BUY" or "SELL" signal to print.

Require DTL for Buy? (Checkbox):

What it does: By default, this is OFF. When OFF, the script acts as a hybrid: it will trigger a buy if price breaks the Diagonal Down-Trend Line (DTL) OR if it breaks above the baseline EMA.

When to turn it ON: Check this box if you want maximum safety. It forces the script to only buy if a mathematical, multi-point Down-Trend Line exists and is broken. Use this for highly structured swing trades.

Volume Spike Factor (Number, Default: 1.2):

What it does: This dictates how much "Institutional Effort" is required. A value of 1.2 means volume must be 20% higher than the 20-day average. A value of 2.0 means volume must be double the average.

How to tune it: For highly liquid, noisy stocks (like Tesla or Capital A), raise this to 1.5 or 1.8 to filter out fake retail volume. For slower, heavy stocks, leave it at 1.2.

Allow Tiny Wicks? (Checkbox):

What it does: Pure Heikin Ashi theory demands a completely flat bottom (zero lower wick) for a strong uptrend. However, live data feeds often have 1-cent micro-wicks that ruin the signal. This setting mathematically forgives these microscopic errors.

Recommendation: Leave this ON for 99% of your trading.

2. Trend Detection (The Structural Framework)

This section controls how the script maps the architecture of the chart.

Pivot Lookback (Number, Default: 10):

What it does: Tells the array scanner how far left to look to find the major "Peaks" (Pivot Highs) to draw the red dashed Down-Trend Line.

How to tune it: If the red trendline is drawing too erratically, increase this number to 15 or 20. This forces the script to ignore minor bumps and only connect major, multi-week structural highs.

Fallback EMA Trend (Number, Default: 50):

What it does: Determines the length of the yellow baseline trend (Exponential Moving Average). This is your safety net when a stock is moving sideways or parabolic and a DTL cannot be drawn.

How to tune it: 50 is the institutional standard for medium-term swing trading. Change it to 20 for aggressive day-trading or 200 for long-term investing.

3. Dashboard Settings (The Command Center)

Keep your workspace clean. You need to see the price action without data blocking your view.

Position (Dropdown): Move the Master's Dashboard to any of the 6 corners/sides of your screen (Top Right, Bottom Left, Middle Right, etc.).

Size (Dropdown): Choose between Tiny, Small, or Normal. Pro Tip: If you are trading on the TradingView mobile app, set this to "Tiny" so it doesn't cover your candles.

4. Visual Enhancements (The Tape)

Show Integrated Volume Sub-Chart? (Checkbox):

What it does: Toggles the Dynamic Volume Scaler on or off. When ON, it mathematically shrinks the volume bars and the moving average line to fit perfectly into the bottom 15% of your chart.

Recommendation: Keep this ON to visualize the "Effort" without needing to open a separate, screen-wasting volume indicator at the bottom of your monitor.

👨‍🏫 A Final Word from the Developer

Do not fall into the trap of "overfitting." When you backtest this strategy, do not tweak the Volume Spike Factor to 1.47 just because it gave you a 100% win rate in 2024. Markets change. Find robust, logical whole numbers that perform well across all market conditions, and trust and follow whatever SOP you are currently using. This is just to guide you.
